# Aramaic Primacy - The Peshitta

[Projects Home](index.md) | [Aramaic Primacy](AramaicPrimacy.md)

---

## Introduction

In this article, we will look at evidence regarding the Peshitta to show why it does not support the claims by some (but not all[^1]) Aramaic Primacists that the Peshitta represents the original text of the New Testament.

In order for the Peshitta to be the original text of the New Testament, the language of Peshitta needs to be the same dialect of Aramaic as was used by Jesus and his disciples in First Century Palestine (1CP).

In order to understand Aramaic and its dialects better, let’s first have a discussion on the English language for comparison purposes. If someone were to tell you that the novel *To Kill a Mockingbird* was written by Shakespeare because the novel is written in English, and Shakespeare wrote in English, you’d think they were nuts. In addition to all of the other available evidence, you could prove linguistically that the language of *To Kill a Mockingbird* was spoken in the Southeast of the USA during the 20th Century, and thus it was written in the wrong time and wrong place to have been written by Shakespeare who lived in England during the 16th and 17th centuries - and never visited North America.

***This is the exact same situation with Peshitta.***

According to historical linguists, by the time of Christ there was a recognizable difference between Judean, Samaritan and Galilean Aramaic dialects, which along with Damascene Aramaic and Aleppan Aramaic are broadly classified as Old Western Aramaic. The dialects to the North and East of Palestine and stretching from Syria into Mesopotamia and Persia are classified as Old Eastern Aramaic, and include what is referred to as Syriac – a dialect spoken in the area which is now northern Syria and southeastern Turkey.

Note that the dialects of Palestine are classified as Western Aramaic, while Syriac is classified as Eastern Aramaic, indicating Syriac is more similar to the Aramaic of Mesopotamia and Persia than to the Palestinian dialects.

It is important at this point to clearly define the term “Syriac”. During Greek and Roman times, the term Syriac referred to all dialects of Aramaic. However, the modern usage is to define Syriac as the dialects of Aramaic that were spoken in what is now “south eastern Turkey, northern Iraq, northeastern Syria and North western Iran”[^2]. It is the modern usage that I am using in this article.

Evidence that Syriac and Palestinian Aramaic were different languages is shown by the inscriptions on the tomb of Helena of Adiabene, a Jewish convert from Syria who died in Jerusalem around 50 AD. Her tomb is inscribed in both Syriac and Palestinian Aramaic.

The very fact that Peshitta is written in Syriac should, in itself, be cause to surmise that it is not the correct dialect of Aramaic for the original text of the New Testament. However, let’s look even closer for more details...

Around the third century AD, there was a major language shift for both Eastern and Western Aramaic. The Western Aramaic dialects were mostly subsumed into Middle Galilean Aramaic which became the dominant dialect and is the language in which the Talmud is written. The eastern dialects continued to split – Syriac becoming mutually unintelligible with the other dialects to the east as well as further out of sync with the Western Aramaic languages to the south. Middle Syriac experienced its golden age during the 4th through 6th centuries with a large output of liturgical literature.

Because of known language differences, historical linguists can look at the grammar, syntax and vocabulary of a given Aramaic text and identify not only the region where it was produced, but the time period as well. And their analysis of the Peshitta is that it is written in the Edessan dialect of Middle Syriac which was in common use during the above-mentioned 4th through 6th century golden age.

## Language Comparison

For a demonstration on how 1st Century Galilean Aramaic (1CGA) and 5th Century Edessan Syriac (5CES) are different, let’s look at Matthew 26:52 in both dialects, along with comparisons in English and Greek.

### English

**Matthew 26:52 in English:**

We’ll focus on the part of the verse that is in bold print:

> Then said Jesus to him, “Put up again your sword into his place: **for all they that take the sword shall perish with the sword**.”

### Greek

The Greek text is important here, and we’ll come back to it later:

> παντες γαρ οι λαβοντες μαχαιραν εν μαχαιρη απολουνται

**Transcription:** *pantes gar hoi labontes mahairan en mahaire apolountai*

**Translation:** All, therefore, who taking a sword, by a sword they shall die

### Peshitta

In Peshitta (5CES), we have this:

![][image1]

**Transcription:** *kulhun ger hanun da-nsab saife, b’saife n’muthun*

**Translation:** For all of they who take up swords, with swords they shall die.

### First Century Palestinian Aramaic

And for 1CGA we reconstruct the following:

![][image2]

**Transcription:** *bagin kal d’nsab saiyp, b’saiyp yimuthun*

**Translation:** For everyone who took up a sword, by a sword (OR “in the end”) they shall die

Note that an original text of the NT in 1CGA does not exist, so a reconstruction based on known 1CGA grammar and vocabulary was necessary for this demonstration.

### Analysis

Here is a chart comparing the words of the four languages side by side:

| English | Greek | 5CES | 1CGA |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| all | pantes | kulhun | bagin |
| therefore | gar | ger |  |
| those who | hoi | hanun | kal |
| take up | labontes | da-nsab | d’nsab |
| swords (5CES) / sword (1CGA) | mahairan | saife | saiyp |
| with swords (5CES) / by a sword OR in the end (1CGA) | en mahaire | b’saife | b’saiyp |
| they shall die | apolountai | n’muthun | yimuthun |

It is easy to see from this chart how the two Aramaic dialects are similar, but also that they are different. There are three things to point out:

1. There is a pun present in 1CGA which is not present in 5CES. The word *saiyp* can mean either “sword” or “end”. Because of this, there is a pun which shows up in 1CGA where Jesus’ words can mean either “by the sword they shall die” or “in the end they shall die.” This pun does not exist at all in 5CES of Peshitta. It is true that there is a lot of word play which shows up in Peshitta which is not present in Greek. However, there is much more of this kind of word play that shows up in 1CGA, but not in Peshitta.[^3]  
2. The word *ger* is present in Peshitta, but not in 1CGA. The significance of this can been seen if you look at the Greek text and notice that the second word in Greek is *gar*, the same position (second word) as *ger* in Peshitta. This is a Greek word that means “therefore”, “thus”, “so”, and it is a distinctive feature of Greek that this word often shows up as the second word of Greek phrases. This is not, however, a feature of Aramaic, and only shows up in translations of the scriptures from Greek. It was borrowed into Aramaic in a similar manner that the KJV translators switched the natural English word order around to imitate Greek, and used “he, therefore” in some of the texts of the New Testament such as in Galatians 3:5 “He, therefore, that ministereth to you the Spirit, and worketh miracles among you…” This word is present throughout the Peshitta, and only occurs in Peshitta where the word *gar* also occurs in Greek. This is direct proof of Peshitta being translated from Greek.  
3. Compare *n’muthun* (5CES) vs *yimuthun* (1CGA) meaning "they shall die." The ***n’-*** marker in Syriac is the 3rd person masculine imperfective form. Most Aramaic dialects, including Old Syriac spoken during the 1st Century, use the ***yi-*** or ***ye-*** prefix for this form. Starting in the 3rd century, Edessan Syriac started switching the ***yi-*** prefix to ***n’-***, and the change was complete by the 4th century. Historically, only Edessan Syriac used this form. Historical Aramaic linguists use markers like this to positively identify the specific dialect of a particular document or passage. Based on this, we can know for certain that any document which uses this form exclusively has to be in post-4th Century Edessan Syriac. The fact that Peshitta uses the ***n’-*** for exclusively proves that it uses an Aramaic dialect that is from the wrong place and wrong time to have been used by Jesus and the disciples and therefore, this is absolute proof that Peshitta could not possibly have been the original text of the New Testament.[^4]

As if that wasn’t enough, there’s more evidence against Peshitta...

## Details in Peshitta

The Peshitta reading of Mark 15:34 uses ***two different Aramaic dialects***. Quoting from Bauscher’s NT translation: “And in the ninth hour Yeshua cried out in a loud voice, and he said: ‘Eil, Eil, lemana Shabaqthani’, which is, ‘My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?’”

Why the need to translate an Aramaic phrase into Aramaic? The quote of Jesus’ words uses ***eil*** (Palestinian Aramaic) to mean “my God”, while the translation uses the word ***elohi*** (Syriac) to mean “my God”.[^5]

## Other Aramaic Texts

At this point, many Aramaic Primacists will be thinking “But if that’s true, then why are there mention of, references to and quotes from Peshitta prior to the Fourth Century?” The answer is that there aren’t.

Of the early Aramaic-speaking church fathers who quoted Aramaic texts, prior to the 5th Century AD they quoted several different non-Peshitta Aramaic texts (such as [Diatessaron](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diatessaron), [Curetonian Gospels](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curetonian_Gospels) and the [Syriac Sinaiticus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syriac_Sinaiticus), as well as other texts which are different from these three but which have yet to be discovered), ***but never from Peshitta***.

> “From an exhaustive study of the quotations in the earliest Syriac Fathers, and, in particular, of the works of Ephraem Syrus, Professor Burkitt concludes that the Peshitta did not exist in the 4th century. He finds that Ephraem used the Diatessaron in the main as the source of his quotation, although his voluminous writings contain some clear indications that he was aware of the existence of the separate Gospels, and he seems occasionally to have quoted from them. Such quotations as are found in other extant remains of Syriac literature before the 5th century bear a greater resemblance to the readings of the Curetonian and the Sinaitic than to the readings of the Peshitta. Internal and external evidence alike point to the later and revised character of the Peshitta.”

Then, suddenly starting in the fifth Century AD, the church fathers started quoting from Peshitta, and even then, not exclusively, as they continued to quote from, use and make copies of the Curetonian gospels and Diatessaron. In fact, though the Curetonian gospels predate the Peshitta, the earliest remaining Curetonian manuscripts were created in the 6th century.

If Peshitta were the unchanged original, then why are there other, earlier Syriac scriptural documents, and why do the early Syriac church fathers quote these other texts? This points to the Peshitta appearing around the Fifth Century – which is consistent with the time period in which the Aramaic dialect of Peshitta was in use.

Given the fact that there are multiple variant Aramaic texts of the New Testament which were created both before and after Peshitta, it is illogical to think that Peshitta is the original. Why would the Syriac-speaking Christians keep producing multiple different versions if they already had the original?

One additional item to point out here is that 2nd Peter, 2nd and 3rd John, Jude and Revelation were never included in any Peshitta manuscripts. Bauscher admits as such in his translation, and says that he translated these books from the Crawford Aramaic manuscript, and makes vague statements about the language of Crawford closely matching the language of Peshitta, quoting John Gwynn in support of his idea. What he fails to mention, however, is that Gwynn specifically states that the language in the Crawford manuscript closely matches the language of the O.T. Peshitta, but not N.T. Peshitta:

> “... For adequately rendering such a Book into Syriac, therefore, an intimate knowledge of the **Peshitto Old Testament** would be invaluable—almost indespensable. This qualification our translator proves to have possessed in an eminent degree. His work has some closer affinities, bespeaking a more habitual familiarity, with the **Peshitto of the Old Testament than of the New**.”

* John Gwynn, *The Apocalypse of St. John in a Syriac Version Hitherto Unknown*, p. xx, Chapter 2, Section 3, Paragraph 1\. (emphasis supplied)

Isn’t that interesting? The language of Crawford matches the stylisms of the OT Syraic text but not NT, indicating that the OT text uses a different dialect of Syriac than the NT. Now, why would Aramaic Primacists fail to mention that little point? Maybe for the same reason that they misquote Josephus \- because they're covering up evidence that disproves their defective theory.

Based on the above discussion, it can be said with absolute certainty that ***if*** the New Testament had originally been written in Aramaic, the Peshitta ***absolutely does not*** represent the original text.

# Appendix A

Demonstration of **y’** in Palestinian Aramaic vs **n’** in Edessan Syriac

As seen in Brown, Charles Rufus. *An Aramaic Method: Elements of grammar*, p. 54\. This book focuses on the grammar of the Targums which used Palestinian Aramaic. It shows a comparison of the 3rd person Masculine Singular form of the Imperfect verb for Hebrew, Targum Aramaic (spoken Palestinian Aramaic of 1st through 3rd centuries) and Biblical Aramaic (the Aramaic of the Old Testament). All three contain **y’** prefix.

![][image3]

From Marshall, T.J. *Manual of the Aramaic Language of the Palestinian Talmud*. A grammar of Talmudic Aramaic, which is Palestinian Aramaic used in 3rd through 6th Centuries. I have highlighted the Imperfect forms at the bottom. All show the use of the **y’** prefix.

![][image4]

And here is an excerpt from Muraoka, Takamitsu, *Classical Syriac: A Basic Grammar with a Chrestomathy*, 2ed, 2005, p. 48\. It shows the **n’-** prefix (or in his transcription, **ne-**) used for the Imperfective (future) tense.

![][image5]

Here is a copy from Noeldeke, Theodor. *Compendious Syriac Grammar.* 1904, p.104 translated by James Crichton. It also shows the **n’-** prefix for 3rd Person masculine Imperfective form:

![][image6]

There is also available a PDF file of a Syriac Grammar (Robinson, Theodore. *Paradigms and Exercises in Syriac Grammar*, 1962 Clarendon Press). Page 57 introduces the Imperfective form and clearly shows that the 3rd Person Masculine forms use the **n’-** prefix.
